Below is a self-contained HTML file that serves as an interactive API documentation page. It identifies design problems in the proposed endpoints and suggests corrections following REST best practices.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>REST API Documentation</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }
        .accordion {
            max-width: 600px;
            margin: 40px auto;
        }
        .accordion .card {
            margin-bottom: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ddd;
            border-radius: 10px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);
        }
        .accordion .card .card-header {
            padding: 10px;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
            border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        .accordion .card .card-body {
            padding: 10px;
            display: none;
        }
        .accordion .card .card-body.show {
            display: block;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="accordion">
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-header" onclick="toggleCard(this)">Proposed Endpoints</div>
            <div class="card-body show">
                <ul>
                    <li>GET /getUsers</li>
                    <li>POST /user/delete/5</li>
                    <li>GET /createUser?name=Jo</li>
                    <li>PUT /updateAllUsers</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-header" onclick="toggleCard(this)">Design Problems</div>
            <div class="card-body">
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Unnecessary verb in URL:</b> Endpoints like <code>/getUsers</code> and <code>/createUser</code> use HTTP methods that already imply the action (GET, POST, etc.), so the verb in the URL is redundant.</li>
                    <li><b>Incorrect HTTP method:</b> <code>POST /user/delete/5</code> should use a DELETE method instead of POST for deleting resources.</li>
                    <li><b>Inconsistent naming:</b> Endpoints use both plural and singular forms (<code>/getUsers</code> vs <code>/user/delete/5</code>).</li>
                    <li><b>Query parameters for creation:</b> <code>GET /createUser?name=Jo</code> should use a POST method with a JSON body for creating resources, not query parameters.</li>
                    <li><b>Ambiguous update endpoint:</b> <code>PUT /updateAllUsers</code> is too broad and doesn't specify which resource to update.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-header" onclick="toggleCard(this)">Corrected Endpoints</div>
            <div class="card-body">
                <ul>
                    <li><b>GET:</b> <code>/users</code> (Retrieve a list of users)</li>
                    <li><b>DELETE:</b> <code>/users/5</code> (Delete a user by ID)</li>
                    <li><b>POST:</b> <code>/users</code> with JSON body <code>{"name": "Jo"}</code> (Create a new user)</li>
                    <li><b>PUT/PATCH:</b> <code>/users/5</code> with JSON body <code>{"name": "Updated Name"}</code> (Update a user by ID)</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Using proper HTTP methods:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>GET:</b> 200 OK (success), 404 Not Found (if resource doesn't exist)</li>
                    <li><b>POST:</b> 201 Created (success), 400 Bad Request (if request is invalid)</li>
                    <li><b>PUT/PATCH:</b> 200 OK (success), 400 Bad Request (if request is invalid)</li>
                    <li><b>DELETE:</b> 204 No Content (success), 404 Not Found (if resource doesn't exist)</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        function toggleCard(cardHeader) {
            var cardBody = cardHeader.nextElementSibling;
            cardBody.classList.toggle("show");
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

