```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>API Documentation</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }
        .accordion {
            width: 600px;
            margin: 40px auto;
        }
        .accordion button {
            padding: 15px;
            width: 100%;
            text-align: left;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        .accordion button:hover {
            background-color: #ccc;
        }
        .accordion .panel {
            padding: 15px;
            display: none;
        }
        .accordion .active, .accordion .panel {
            display: block;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>API Documentation</h1>
    <div class="accordion">
        <button onclick="togglePanel(this)">Original Endpoints and Design Problems</button>
        <div class="panel">
            <h2>Original Endpoints:</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>GET /getUsers</li>
                <li>POST /user/delete/5</li>
                <li>GET /createUser?name=Jo</li>
                <li>PUT /updateAllUsers</li>
            </ul>
            <h2>Design Problems:</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>Inconsistent naming conventions (e.g., /getUsers, /user/delete/5)</li>
                <li>Incorrect HTTP methods:
                    <ul>
                        <li>DELETE operation using POST method</li>
                        <li>CREATE operation using GET method</li>
                        <li>UPDATE operation using PUT method for all users</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>Missing resource identifier for UPDATE operation</li>
                <li>Query parameters in path for CREATE operation</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="accordion">
        <button onclick="togglePanel(this)">Corrected Endpoints</button>
        <div class="panel">
            <h2>Corrected Endpoints:</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>GET /users (Retrieve a list of all users)</li>
                <li>DELETE /users/5 (Delete a user with ID 5)</li>
                <li>POST /users (Create a new user)<br>
                    <code>Request Body: { "name": "Jo" }</code>
                </li>
                <li>PUT /users/5 (Update a user with ID 5)<br>
                    <code>Request Body: { "name": "Updated Name" }</code>
                </li>
            </ul>
            <h2>HTTP Status Codes:</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>200 OK (Successful response)</li>
                <li>201 Created (Resource created successfully)</li>
                <li>204 No Content (Resource deleted successfully)</li>
                <li>400 Bad Request (Invalid request)</li>
                <li>404 Not Found (Resource not found)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        function togglePanel(button) {
            var panel = button.nextElementSibling;
            if (panel.style.display === "block") {
                panel.style.display = "none";
            } else {
                panel.style.display = "block";
            }
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This HTML file provides an interactive API documentation page with expandable sections. It identifies design problems in the original endpoints and presents corrected endpoints following REST best practices with proper HTTP methods, consistent naming, and status codes. The corrected endpoints are styled as a professional API reference.

**Key Takeaways:**

*   **Consistent Naming:** Use plural nouns for resource collections (e.g., /users).
*   **Correct HTTP Methods:**
    *   **GET:** Retrieve a resource.
    *   **POST:** Create a new resource.
    *   **PUT:** Update an existing resource.
    *   **DELETE:** Delete a resource.
*   **Resource Identifiers:** Include resource identifiers in the path for UPDATE and DELETE operations.
*   **Query Parameters:** Avoid using query parameters in the path for CREATE operations; instead, use the request body.
*   **HTTP Status Codes:** Use standard HTTP status codes to indicate the outcome of a request.

