Below is a single self-contained HTML file that serves as an interactive API documentation page. It addresses the issues with the provided API endpoints and adheres to proper REST conventions. I've used HTML, CSS, and JavaScript to create an expandable/collapsible section for each endpoint.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>API Documentation</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }
        .endpoint {
            margin-bottom: 20px;
            border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc;
        }
        .endpoint h2 {
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        .endpoint .details {
            display: none;
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
            background-color: #f9f9f9;
        }
        .endpoint .details.show {
            display: block;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>API Documentation</h1>

    <div class="endpoint">
        <h2>GET /users</h2>
        <div class="details">
            <p><strong>Retrieve a list of all users</strong></p>
            <p>Returns a JSON array of user objects.</p>
            <pre><code>{
  "users": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "name": "John Doe"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "name": "Jane Doe"
    }
  ]
}</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="endpoint">
        <h2>POST /users</h2>
        <div class="details">
            <p><strong>Create a new user</strong></p>
            <p>Request Body:</p>
            <pre><code>{
  "name": "Jo"
}</code></pre>
            <p>Returns a JSON object with the newly created user's details.</p>
            <pre><code>{
  "id": 3,
  "name": "Jo"
}</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="endpoint">
        <h2>DELETE /users/:id</h2>
        <div class="details">
            <p><strong>Delete a user by ID</strong></p>
            <p>Returns a JSON object with a success message.</p>
            <pre><code>{
  "message": "User deleted successfully"
}</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="endpoint">
        <h2>PUT /users/:id</h2>
        <div class="details">
            <p><strong>Update a user's details</strong></p>
            <p>Request Body:</p>
            <pre><code>{
  "name": "Updated Name"
}</code></pre>
            <p>Returns a JSON object with the updated user's details.</p>
            <pre><code>{
  "id": 1,
  "name": "Updated Name"
}</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        const endpoints = document.querySelectorAll('.endpoint h2');
        endpoints.forEach((endpoint) => {
            endpoint.addEventListener('click', () => {
                const details = endpoint.nextElementSibling;
                details.classList.toggle('show');
            });
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

The issues addressed in this API design are:

1.  **Inconsistent endpoint naming**:
    *   `GET /getUsers` is changed to `GET /users` to follow REST conventions.
2.  **Incorrect HTTP method**:
    *   `POST /user/delete/5` is changed to `DELETE /users/:id` to use the correct HTTP method for deletion.
3.  **Query parameters for creation**:
    *   `GET /createUser?name=Jo` is changed to `POST /users` with a request body to pass user details, as creation should typically use a POST request with a request body.
4.  **Ambiguous update endpoint**:
    *   `PUT /updateAllUsers` is changed to `PUT /users/:id` to update a specific user's details.

The provided HTML file includes interactive sections for each endpoint, allowing you to expand and collapse the details. The API design adheres to proper REST conventions and provides clear documentation for each endpoint.
